    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="943"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d943">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.01B11 Registration—Ovakimian, Gaik
                    (Dr.)/27</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Acting Attorney General</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Biddle</hi>
                    </persName>
                    <note n="9" xml:id="d943fn9">Francis Biddle.</note>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-18">July 18,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Biddle</hi>: I wish to refer to Mr. Berge’s
                    letter of June 27, 1941 (WB: DEB: 146–7–40) enclosing a communication from the
                    United States Attorney at New York City concerning the case of <hi rend="italic"
                        >United States</hi> v. <hi rend="italic">Gaik B. Ovakimian</hi>.<note n="10"
                        xml:id="d943fn10">Neither printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In view of certain important considerations of an international character, this
                    Department is of the opinion that it would be to the public interest to suspend
                    the case against Mr. Ovakimian on condition that he leave the United States as
                    soon as possible and never return.</p>
                <p>It would be appreciated, therefore, if you would inform the authorities of this
                    Government conducting the prosecution of Mr. Ovakimian of the opinion of this
                    Department as expressed above.</p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sumner Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
